hopobject.body: History ic cephalexin and birth control For even the most confident employees, mustering up the courage to ask for a raise can be a struggle. It's not that they think they don't deserve it (they do). But the unknown of their boss's answer is too great. "[Employees] are worried that they will appear to be presumptuous and pushy and that the answer will be no. And that it's sort of a negative step on a career track to have a setback like that," says G. Richard Shell, academic director of The Wharton School's Executive Negotiation Workshop at the University of Pennsylvania and author of "Bargaining for Advantage: Negotiation Strategies for Reasonable People."
